{"parentUuid":"d926c488-6a7d-4247-a2c7-08b5b9639ed8","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"795b6292-899f-43d1-822d-8e0cc35d6b7d","agentId":"a1cd25545786ab187","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01VosLbQAbSfATzf72ATvdgi","type":"tool_result","content":"<persisted-output>\nOutput too large (35.5KB). Full output saved to: C:\\Users\\brett\\.claude\\projects\\c--Users-brett-OneDrive-Documents-GitHub-meterly-pipeline-test\\d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a\\tool-results\\b93sbriuu.txt\n\nPreview (first 2KB):\ndiff --git a/.github/workflows/pipeline-ci.yml b/.github/workflows/pipeline-ci.yml\nindex 600d34e..99912a9 100644\n--- a/.github/workflows/pipeline-ci.yml\n+++ b/.github/workflows/pipeline-ci.yml\n@@ -63,10 +63,11 @@ jobs:\n       - name: Build\n         run: poetry run python -c \"import src.main\"\n       - name: Test with coverage (floor = the local gate's figure)\n-        run: poetry run pytest --cov=src --cov-branch\n-        # Fail under <COVERAGE_FLOOR>% combined lines — the same figure the local deploy\n-        # gate rides. Branch coverage: surface in the job summary, do NOT gate (mirrors\n-        # the local posture; see test-conventions).\n+        run: poetry run pytest --cov=src --cov-branch --cov-fail-under=85\n+        # Fail under 85% combined lines — CLAUDE.md's done-bar figure (\"tests pass at\n+        # >= 85% coverage\"), the same figure the local deploy gate rides. Branch\n+        # coverage: surface in the job summary, do NOT gate (mirrors the local\n+        # posture; see test-conventions).\n \n   # mutation — U-22: run mutation testing HERE, on the Linux runner, not on the author's\n   # host. mutmut needs a POSIX environment (WSL on Windows), so the local pipeline honestly\ndiff --git a/PROJECT.md b/PROJECT.md\nindex ef22d91..bc052b4 100644\n--- a/PROJECT.md\n+++ b/PROJECT.md\n@@ -1,6 +1,4 @@\n-Feature: per-customer metric quotas.\n-- PUT /v1/quotas (admin-scoped API key) sets {customer_id, metric, limit_per_window}.\n-- POST /v1/events returns 429 with a quota error envelope when the current-window rollup for that customer/metric would exceed the quota. Customers without a quota are unlimited (no behavior change).\n-- One expand-only migration: a quotas table.\n-- Existing perf budget applies: p95 < 50 ms under load on POST /v1/events.\n+Feature: usage CSV export.\n+- GET /v1/usage/export returns the caller's usage rollups (customer_id, metric, window_start, total_quantity) as CSV.\n+- Existing API-key auth applies. No behavior change to any existing endpoint.\n...\n</persisted-output>","is_error":false}]},"uuid":"73eddf14-4a5f-4ec1-804d-bc984b64b16d","timestamp":"2026-07-09T20:47:41.953Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"d926c488-6a7d-4247-a2c7-08b5b9639ed8","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/usage-export"}
{"parentUuid":"73eddf14-4a5f-4ec1-804d-bc984b64b16d","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a1cd25545786ab187","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011Ccs95dSBs5uWzTFCweWPn","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Vbyi3iM1H2NFwPDTTvzMAD","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\brett\\.claude\\projects\\c--Users-brett-OneDrive-Documents-GitHub-meterly-pipeline-test\\d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a\\tool-results\\b93sbriuu.txt"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1368,"cache_read_input_tokens":17585,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1368,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":55,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011Ccs95cXN8dFPPoHKtJY2k","attributionAgent":"Explore","attributionSkill":"code-review","type":"assistant","uuid":"b71cb34b-2e55-4749-b0d7-e9b3b5ccb9b6","timestamp":"2026-07-09T20:47:44.257Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/usage-export"}
{"parentUuid":"b71cb34b-2e55-4749-b0d7-e9b3b5ccb9b6","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"795b6292-899f-43d1-822d-8e0cc35d6b7d","agentId":"a1cd25545786ab187","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Vbyi3iM1H2NFwPDTTvzMAD","type":"tool_result","content":"1\tdiff --git a/.github/workflows/pipeline-ci.yml b/.github/workflows/pipeline-ci.yml\n2\tindex 600d34e..99912a9 100644\n3\t--- a/.github/workflows/pipeline-ci.yml\n4\t+++ b/.github/workflows/pipeline-ci.yml\n5\t@@ -63,10 +63,11 @@ jobs:\n6\t       - name: Build\n7\t         run: poetry run python -c \"import src.main\"\n8\t       - name: Test with coverage (floor = the local gate's figure)\n9\t-        run: poetry run pytest --cov=src --cov-branch\n10\t-        # Fail under <COVERAGE_FLOOR>% combined lines — the same figure the local deploy\n11\t-        # gate rides. Branch coverage: surface in the job summary, do NOT gate (mirrors\n12\t-        # the local posture; see test-conventions).\n13\t+        run: poetry run pytest --cov=src --cov-branch --cov-fail-under=85\n14\t+        # Fail under 85% combined lines — CLAUDE.md's done-bar figure (\"tests pass at\n15\t+        # >= 85% coverage\"), the same figure the local deploy gate rides. Branch\n16\t+        # coverage: surface in the job summary, do NOT gate (mirrors the local\n17\t+        # posture; see test-conventions).\n18\t \n19\t   # mutation — U-22: run mutation testing HERE, on the Linux runner, not on the author's\n20\t   # host. mutmut needs a POSIX environment (WSL on Windows), so the local pipeline honestly\n21\tdiff --git a/PROJECT.md b/PROJECT.md\n22\tindex ef22d91..bc052b4 100644\n23\t--- a/PROJECT.md\n24\t+++ b/PROJECT.md\n25\t@@ -1,6 +1,4 @@\n26\t-Feature: per-customer metric quotas.\n27\t-- PUT /v1/quotas (admin-scoped API key) sets {customer_id, metric, limit_per_window}.\n28\t-- POST /v1/events returns 429 with a quota error envelope when the current-window rollup for that customer/metric would exceed the quota. Customers without a quota are unlimited (no behavior change).\n29\t-- One expand-only migration: a quotas table.\n30\t-- Existing perf budget applies: p95 < 50 ms under load on POST /v1/events.\n31\t+Feature: usage CSV export.\n32\t+- GET /v1/usage/export returns the caller's usage rollups (customer_id, metric, window_start, total_quantity) as CSV.\n33\t+- Existing API-key auth applies. No behavior change to any existing endpoint.\n34\t Design source: none.\n35\tdiff --git a/docs/system_architecture.md b/docs/system_architecture.md\n36\tindex d0b6170..7b98b3c 100644\n37\t--- a/docs/system_architecture.md\n38\t+++ b/docs/system_architecture.md\n39\t@@ -3,9 +3,10 @@\n40\t ## Overview\n41\t \n42\t Meterly ingests metered usage events, serves aggregated per-customer/metric\n43\t-counters, and enforces admin-set per-customer, per-metric usage caps\n44\t-(\"quotas\"). Three authenticated HTTP endpoints, one PostgreSQL database, one\n45\t-Redis rate-limit store, running as a Docker container on ECS Fargate behind an ALB.\n46\t+counters (single-bucket read or a streamed CSV export), and enforces\n47\t+admin-set per-customer, per-metric usage caps (\"quotas\"). Four authenticated\n48\t+HTTP endpoints, one PostgreSQL database, one Redis rate-limit store, running\n49\t+as a Docker container on ECS Fargate behind an ALB.\n50\t \n51\t ```\n52\t Client --HTTPS+API key--> ALB --> FastAPI (ECS Fargate, >=2 tasks)\n53\t@@ -23,6 +24,7 @@ flowchart LR\n54\t     FastAPI -->|\"require_api_key: cache hit or Argon2id verify\"| AuthDB[(RDS PostgreSQL: api_keys)]\n55\t     FastAPI -->|\"POST /v1/events: insert + quota check + rollup upsert\"| EventsDB[(RDS PostgreSQL: events / usage_rollup / quotas)]\n56\t     FastAPI -->|\"GET /v1/usage: read rollup\"| EventsDB\n57\t+    FastAPI -->|\"GET /v1/usage/export: pre-flight COUNT + streamed SELECT\"| EventsDB\n58\t     FastAPI -->|\"PUT /v1/quotas: upsert cap\"| EventsDB\n59\t     FastAPI -->|\"DB credential fetch\"| Secrets[Secrets Manager]\n60\t     FastAPI -->|\"traces/logs/errors\"| Observability[\"CloudWatch / X-Ray / Sentry\"]\n61\t@@ -65,6 +67,63 @@ and reads a single `usage_rollup` row scoped by the caller's `api_key_id`\n62\t (`src/services/usage_service.py`, `src/repositories/usage_repo.py`). A missing\n63\t bucket returns zeros with 200, never 404.\n64\t \n65\t+## Request flow — `GET /v1/usage/export`\n66\t+\n67\t+Same auth/throttle/error stack, plus a two-phase pre-flight-then-stream\n68\t+design (`src/api/routes/usage_export.py`,\n69\t+`src/services/usage_export_service.py`,\n70\t+`src/repositories/usage_repo.py`):\n71\t+\n72\t+1. `UsageExportQueryParams` validates the optional `customer_id`/`metric`/\n73\t+   `from`/`to` filters (`src/api/schemas/usage_export.py`) — reuses the same\n74\t+   `CustomerId`/`Metric` anchored allowlists as `events.py` and the same\n75\t+   `[now-90d, now+1h]` bound idiom as `usage.py`'s `window`, applied here to\n76\t+   a `[from, to]` range.\n77\t+2. **Pre-flight cap check** (`prepare_export`): a `COUNT(*)` over the\n78\t+   caller's rows (scoped by `api_key_id` first, plus the optional filters)\n79\t+   inside its own transaction. Over 100,000 rows -> 422\n80\t+   `validation_failed`, logged at `warn` (`usage.export.rejected`). This\n81\t+   runs, and fully resolves, *before* any response byte — once a\n82\t+   `StreamingResponse` is constructed the status line is already 200 and the\n83\t+   cap decision can no longer cleanly 422. Any *other* (non-cap) error here\n84\t+   propagates uncaught to the error-envelope boundary: a fail-closed generic\n85\t+   500, transaction rolled back, no stream ever started.\n86\t+3. **Stream** (`stream_export_csv`): a `StreamingResponse` whose body\n87\t+   generator is pulled by Starlette only after the handler returns, so it\n88\t+   opens its **own** tenant-scoped transaction (the `SET LOCAL\n89\t+   app.current_api_key_id` RLS-backstop setting and the server-side cursor\n90\t+   both need to stay valid for the whole stream, not just the pre-flight\n91\t+   phase). Yields the header row first, always (an empty result is a 200\n92\t+   header-only CSV, never 404), then one CSV-encoded row per record from\n93\t+   `stream_usage_rollups` (`ORDER BY window_start, customer_id, metric` — a\n94\t+   fixed literal, never client-derived — `LIMIT 100000`), each row written\n95\t+   into a reused `io.StringIO` via stdlib `csv.writer` (RFC 4180, CRLF,\n96\t+   `QUOTE_MINIMAL`) and drained to bytes immediately — constant memory\n97\t+   throughout. `customer_id`/`metric` text cells pass through\n98\t+   `src/api/csv_export.py`'s `escape_csv_text_cell` (the OWASP\n99\t+   formula-injection defense: a leading `= + - @ \\t \\r` gets a `'` prefix)\n100\t+   *before* reaching the writer; numeric/timestamp cells are formatted but\n101\t+   never escaped (they're server-generated, never attacker-controlled).\n102\t+   Logs exactly one `usage.export` audit event in a `finally` block\n103\t+   (`rowCount`, `capped`, `completed`, filter-presence booleans — never the\n104\t+   raw `customer_id`/`metric` values), so a client disconnect or a mid-stream\n105\t+   DB error still records what was actually sent.\n106\t+\n107\t+Response headers: `Content-Type: text/csv; charset=utf-8`,\n108\t+`Content-Disposition: attachment; filename=\"usage-export-<UTC\n109\t+timestamp>.csv\"` (no tenant identifier in the filename), plus the inherited\n110\t+`nosniff` and (via the existing `/v1/usage`-prefix rule in\n111\t+`src/api/middleware.py`) `Cache-Control: no-store`.\n112\t+\n113\t+**Accepted risk — mid-stream failure truncates the CSV.** Once the 200\n114\t+status line and header bytes are on the wire, an unhandled error partway\n115\t+through the stream can no longer be converted to a clean error envelope; the\n116\t+client sees a truncated download it can re-request. This is strictly the\n117\t+*post-200* case — the pre-flight `COUNT` phase above is fully recoverable\n118\t+and does return the generic 500 envelope. Bounded by the row cap + Tier-2\n119\t+throttle + connection-pool sizing; batched keyset pagination is the future\n120\t+mitigation if this needs closing further.\n121\t+\n122\t ## Request flow — `PUT /v1/quotas`\n123\t \n124\t Admin-scoped create-or-replace of a per-customer, per-metric usage cap.\n125\t@@ -171,3 +230,34 @@ OTel/Sentry wiring-at-construction-time change vs. the plan's original\n126\t lifespan-hook placement. See `plan.md`'s \"Open questions\" section for the\n127\t accepted risks around key-revocation latency, `api_key_id`-as-tenant-scope,\n128\t and the Postgres app-role bootstrap's CI-network-reachability prerequisite.\n129\t+\n130\t+**`GET /v1/usage/export` p95 at the 100,000-row cap — resolved (was: plan\n131\t+§\"Open questions\" #1, originally unconfirmed).** The first measured p95\n132\t+(~10.7s locally / 25.2s on testing's independent re-measure) was root-caused\n133\t+during debugging to the streaming generator yielding **one chunk per row**:\n134\t+the app's four nested `BaseHTTPMiddleware` layers (`src/main.py`) each\n135\t+re-pump every streamed chunk through their own anyio memory-object-stream, so\n136\t+cost scaled with `chunk_count x middleware_layers` and dominated wall-clock\n137\t+time at the 100k-row cap — not CSV encoding or DB query time, which were both\n138\t+sub-second in isolation. Three within-design fixes closed the gap (see\n139\t+`.pipeline/debug-notes.md` for the full isolation profiling):\n140\t+- `src/services/usage_export_service.py` batches `_ROWS_PER_CHUNK = 1000`\n141\t+  encoded rows per yielded chunk (was one row per chunk) — the primary lever,\n142\t+  cutting chunk count ~1,000x at the cap while staying constant-memory (the\n143\t+  buffer holds at most one batch).\n144\t+- `src/api/csv_export.py`'s `escape_csv_text_cell` replaced its per-character\n145\t+  strip loop with a precompiled `str.translate` deletion table (semantics\n146\t+  verified identical across all C0/DEL codepoints).\n147\t+- `src/repositories/usage_repo.py`'s `stream_usage_rollups` tunes the\n148\t+  server-side cursor with `execution_options(yield_per=_STREAM_FETCH_BATCH)`\n149\t+  (`_STREAM_FETCH_BATCH = 5000`) — more rows fetched per DB round-trip,\n150\t+  cursor still never abandoned.\n151\t+\n152\t+Net effect: p95 dropped from ~10.7s to a stable **p95 ~1.6-2.1s** (10-sample\n153\t+measurement). The original 500ms target proved unreachable within the\n154\t+approved constant-memory-streaming design (an irreducible ~0.85-1.0s floor\n155\t+from the server-side cursor drain + per-row CSV encoding, even discounting\n156\t+middleware). The human confirmed a revised, binding budget of **p95 <=\n157\t+3,000ms at the 100,000-row cap** at the 2026-07-09 escalation, which\n158\t+`tests/integration/test_usage_export_perf.py` now hard-asserts (AC16); this\n159\t+session's re-run measured p95 1,643.87ms, comfortably under the bound.\n160\tdiff --git a/src/api/README.md b/src/api/README.md\n161\tindex 11ca706..d49e044 100644\n162\t--- a/src/api/README.md\n163\t+++ b/src/api/README.md\n164\t@@ -9,12 +9,15 @@ HTTP API layer: FastAPI route handlers, request/response schemas (Pydantic v2),\n165\t | File / Module | Responsibility |\n166\t |---|---|\n167\t | `routes/events.py` | `POST /v1/events` handler; calls `events_service.create_event`. |\n168\t-| `routes/usage.py` | `GET /v1/usage` handler; calls `usage_service.read_usage`. |\n169\t+| `routes/usage.py` | `GET /v1/usage` handler; calls `usage_service.get_usage`. |\n170\t+| `routes/usage_export.py` | `GET /v1/usage/export` handler; two-phase pre-flight row-cap check (`usage_export_service.prepare_export`) then a `StreamingResponse` body (`usage_export_service.stream_export_csv`). Kept in its own module (not added to `usage.py`) so `GET /v1/usage`'s code path stays untouched. Declares explicit `responses=` OpenAPI metadata (200 `text/csv`, 422) since a `StreamingResponse` has no `response_model` to introspect. |\n171\t | `routes/quotas.py` | `PUT /v1/quotas` handler; composes auth -> Tier-2 throttle -> an `admin`-scope gate (403 `forbidden` otherwise) -> `quota_service.upsert_tenant_quota`. |\n172\t | `routes/health.py` | `GET /health` (liveness, no dependencies) and `GET /health/ready` (readiness, DB + migration check). |\n173\t-| `schemas/events.py` | Pydantic models for POST /v1/events request and response; `extra='forbid'` contract enforcement. |\n174\t+| `schemas/events.py` | Pydantic models for POST /v1/events request and response; `extra='forbid'` contract enforcement. Also defines the `CustomerId`/`Metric` anchored-allowlist `constr` types reused by `schemas/usage.py` and `schemas/usage_export.py`. |\n175\t | `schemas/usage.py` | Pydantic models for GET /v1/usage request (query parameters) and response. |\n176\t+| `schemas/usage_export.py` | `UsageExportQueryParams` for GET /v1/usage/export — optional `customer_id`/`metric`/`from`/`to` filters (`from` bound via a Pydantic alias to the `from_` field, since `from` is a Python keyword), the same `[now-90d, now+1h]` range bound as `usage.py`, `extra='forbid'`. |\n177\t | `schemas/quotas.py` | Pydantic models for PUT /v1/quotas request (`customer_id`, `metric`, `limit_per_window`, `extra='forbid'`) and response (echo shape). |\n178\t+| `csv_export.py` | The CSV encoding facade for the export route: `EXPORT_HEADER`, `escape_csv_text_cell` (the OWASP CSV/formula-injection escape, applied at the encoding sink independent of upstream ingest validation), and the `format_window_start`/`format_total_quantity` value formatters. |\n179\t | `middleware.py` | Request-ID / trace-ID assignment, security headers (HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options), CORS (allows GET/POST/PUT). |\n180\t | `errors.py` | Error-envelope boundary: catches all unhandled exceptions and returns `{error:{code,message,requestId}}` with no stack/secret leakage. `AppError` lets a raised exception carry an explicit `app_code` (e.g. `quota_exceeded`) that overrides the default status->code map — needed because 429 is shared by two distinct codes (`rate_limited` vs `quota_exceeded`). |\n181\t \n182\t@@ -22,14 +25,15 @@ HTTP API layer: FastAPI route handlers, request/response schemas (Pydantic v2),\n183\t \n184\t **Public surface:**\n185\t - Imported by `src/main.py` to register routes with FastAPI.\n186\t-- Exposes `get_app()` function which returns the fully-configured FastAPI instance.\n187\t+- Exposes `create_app()` function (in `src/main.py`) which returns the fully-configured FastAPI instance.\n188\t \n189\t **Dependencies:**\n190\t - `middleware.py` and `errors.py` are registered once at app construction (middleware stack + exception handler).\n191\t - Each route handler uses `require_api_key` guard from `src/auth` to enforce authentication.\n192\t-- Route handlers call `src/services.{events_service, usage_service}` to execute business logic.\n193\t+- Route handlers call `src/services.{events_service, usage_service, usage_export_service}` to execute business logic.\n194\t - Schemas validate request bodies/parameters; malformed input raises Pydantic `ValidationError` → 422.\n195\t - Middleware and error boundary run for all routes, ensuring every response has proper headers and envelope shape.\n196\t+- `routes/usage_export.py` and `services/usage_export_service.py` both import `csv_export.py` for the column contract and formula-escape (never inlined at either call site).\n197\t \n198\t **Middleware ordering (in `main.py`):**\n199\t 1. Request-ID / trace (outermost) — sets correlation context for all downstream logging.\n200\t@@ -49,6 +53,7 @@ HTTP API layer: FastAPI route handlers, request/response schemas (Pydantic v2),\n201\t - `quantity` is a decimal > 0 (no zero or negative); `idempotency_key` is alphanumeric + underscore/dash.\n202\t - GET `/v1/usage` requires a timezone-aware ISO-8601 `window` parameter within 90 days past to 1 hour future (naive datetimes rejected).\n203\t - PUT `/v1/quotas`: `limit_per_window` is an integer `>= 1` (`<= 1e15`, BIGINT-safe); `customer_id`/`metric` reuse the same anchored allowlists as events; unknown fields (including a client-supplied `api_key_id`/`scope`) are rejected outright.\n204\t+- GET `/v1/usage/export`: every filter (`customer_id`, `metric`, `from`, `to`) is optional; `from`/`to` follow the same timezone-aware, `[now-90d, now+1h]`-bounded contract as `usage.py`'s `window`, plus `from <= to`; unknown query params (including a client-supplied `api_key_id`) are rejected outright. A result exceeding 100,000 rows is rejected 422 *before* any response byte (a pre-flight `COUNT`, not a mid-stream cutoff).\n205\t \n206\t **Error handling:**\n207\t - Authentication failures (missing/invalid key) → 401/403 before handlers run.\n208\tdiff --git a/src/main.py b/src/main.py\n209\tindex 1215395..624b911 100644\n210\t--- a/src/main.py\n211\t+++ b/src/main.py\n212\t@@ -29,6 +29,7 @@ from src.api.routes.events import router as events_router\n213\t from src.api.routes.health import router as health_router\n214\t from src.api.routes.quotas import router as quotas_router\n215\t from src.api.routes.usage import router as usage_router\n216\t+from src.api.routes.usage_export import router as usage_export_router\n217\t from src.config.settings import get_settings\n218\t from src.db.session import dispose_engine\n219\t from src.logging import get_logger\n220\t@@ -85,6 +86,7 @@ def create_app() -> FastAPI:\n221\t     app.include_router(health_router)\n222\t     app.include_router(events_router)\n223\t     app.include_router(usage_router)\n224\t+    app.include_router(usage_export_router)\n225\t     app.include_router(quotas_router)\n226\t \n227\t     # Must run after routes are mounted (FastAPIInstrumentor introspects them)\n228\tdiff --git a/src/repositories/README.md b/src/repositories/README.md\n229\tindex 9400c70..fb6b4da 100644\n230\t--- a/src/repositories/README.md\n231\t+++ b/src/repositories/README.md\n232\t@@ -8,15 +8,15 @@ Data access layer: SQL queries with parameterization, row-level scoping (by auth\n233\t \n234\t | File / Module | Responsibility |\n235\t |---|---|\n236\t-| `events_repo.py` | `create_or_replay_event(api_key_id, customer_id, metric, quantity, idempotency_key, window_start)` — INSERT ... ON CONFLICT ... DO NOTHING (idempotency). Also `upsert_rollup()` (called only on insert success). |\n237\t-| `usage_repo.py` | `read_usage(api_key_id, customer_id, metric, window_start)` — SELECT from `usage_rollup` scoped by `api_key_id`. Returns None if missing (caller handles zero conversion). |\n238\t+| `events_repo.py` | `insert_event_if_new(session, *, api_key_id, customer_id, metric, quantity, idempotency_key, window_start)` — `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (api_key_id, idempotency_key) DO NOTHING`, returning `None` on a duplicate. `find_event_by_idempotency_key(session, *, api_key_id, idempotency_key)` — reads back the original row on a duplicate replay. `increment_usage_rollup(session, *, api_key_id, customer_id, metric, window_start, quantity)` — the rollup upsert, called only after `insert_event_if_new` returns a row. |\n239\t+| `usage_repo.py` | `find_usage_rollup(api_key_id, customer_id, metric, window_start)` — SELECT from `usage_rollup` scoped by `api_key_id`. Returns None if missing (caller handles zero conversion). `count_usage_rollups(api_key_id, customer_id=None, metric=None, window_from=None, window_to=None)` — the export's pre-flight row-cap count over the same optional filters. `stream_usage_rollups(api_key_id, ..., limit)` — the export's server-side-cursor stream (`session.stream(...)`, yields `UsageRollupExportRecord`), ordered by a **fixed literal** `ORDER BY window_start, customer_id, metric` (never client-derived) with `LIMIT`. The count and stream queries share a `_export_filter_clause_and_params` helper so their WHERE clauses can never drift apart. |\n240\t | `api_keys_repo.py` | `find_active_key_by_key_id(key_id)` — SELECT from `api_keys` by public `key_id` (used by auth cache miss); returns the full row including `scope`. `create_api_key(..., scope=\"ingest\")` — the only key-provisioning path. |\n241\t | `quotas_repo.py` | `upsert_quota(...)` — `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (api_key_id, customer_id, metric) DO UPDATE ... RETURNING (xmax = 0) AS inserted`, reporting create-vs-replace in one round-trip. `read_tenant_quota_state_locked(...)` — the atomic check-then-decide: locks the quota row (`FOR UPDATE`), then reads the current-window rollup total as a **separate, fresh** statement (see *Notes* below for why). Returns `None` when no quota exists (unlimited, no lock taken). |\n242\t \n243\t ## Relationships\n244\t \n245\t **Public surface:**\n246\t-- Imported by `src/services.{events_service, usage_service, quota_service}` to execute queries.\n247\t+- Imported by `src/services.{events_service, usage_service, usage_export_service, quota_service}` to execute queries.\n248\t - `api_keys_repo` is also imported by `src/auth.api_key` (credential lookup on cache miss).\n249\t - `quotas_repo` is imported by both `quota_service` (the upsert) and `events_service` (the read-and-decide).\n250\t \n251\t@@ -32,13 +32,13 @@ Data access layer: SQL queries with parameterization, row-level scoping (by auth\n252\t - If a query accidentally omits the `api_key_id` filter, RLS blocks it at the database level (defense-in-depth).\n253\t \n254\t **Field projections (minimal surface):**\n255\t-- `create_or_replay_event` returns only `{event_id, customer_id, metric, quantity, window_start, idempotent_replay}` — not the full row (which includes `created_at`, `event_time`, `api_key_id`).\n256\t-- `read_usage` returns only `{customer_id, metric, window_start, total_quantity, event_count}` — not internal bookkeeping (`updated_at`, `api_key_id`).\n257\t+- `insert_event_if_new` / `find_event_by_idempotency_key` return an `EventRecord{id, api_key_id, customer_id, metric, quantity, idempotency_key, window_start}` — the service layer maps this to the minimal public response shape (not the full row is a service-layer concern, not a repo-layer projection).\n258\t+- `find_usage_rollup` returns only `{total_quantity, event_count}` — not internal bookkeeping (`updated_at`, `api_key_id`).\n259\t+- `stream_usage_rollups` yields `UsageRollupExportRecord{customer_id, metric, window_start, total_quantity}` — exactly the four exported columns, never `event_count`, `updated_at`, or `api_key_id`.\n260\t - `api_keys_repo.get_by_key_id` returns the full row (needed by auth for `secret_hash`, `rate_limit_per_sec`, `revoked_at`).\n261\t \n262\t **Constraint enforcement:**\n263\t-- `create_or_replay_event` relies on the `UNIQUE (api_key_id, idempotency_key)` constraint at the DB level to detect duplicates.\n264\t-- If a duplicate key is encountered, PostgreSQL raises an `IntegrityError` (caught by service layer) → the service reads the original row instead.\n265\t+- `insert_event_if_new` relies on the `UNIQUE (api_key_id, idempotency_key)` constraint plus `ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING` (not a caught `IntegrityError`) — a duplicate insert returns no row, evaluated atomically by PostgreSQL. If no row is returned, the service calls `find_event_by_idempotency_key` to read the original row instead.\n266\t - `quantity > 0` and other domain constraints are enforced by CHECK constraints in the schema (verified at insert time).\n267\t \n268\t ## Notes\n269\tdiff --git a/src/repositories/usage_repo.py b/src/repositories/usage_repo.py\n270\tindex 816cee0..3d7ff82 100644\n271\t--- a/src/repositories/usage_repo.py\n272\t+++ b/src/repositories/usage_repo.py\n273\t@@ -1,11 +1,12 @@\n274\t \"\"\"Repository for reading `usage_rollup` — the O(1) aggregate lookup behind\n275\t-`GET /v1/usage`.\n276\t+`GET /v1/usage`, and the count/stream queries behind `GET /v1/usage/export`.\n277\t \n278\t Reads the pre-aggregated counter rather than summing `events` live, which is\n279\t what keeps the GET p95 budget bounded as ingest volume grows (see the plan's\n280\t \"why reading the rollup\" writeup).\n281\t \"\"\"\n282\t \n283\t+from collections.abc import AsyncIterator\n284\t from dataclasses import dataclass\n285\t from datetime import datetime\n286\t from decimal import Decimal\n287\t@@ -56,3 +57,136 @@ async def find_usage_rollup(\n288\t     if row is None:\n289\t         return None\n290\t     return UsageRollupRecord(total_quantity=row[\"total_quantity\"], event_count=row[\"event_count\"])\n291\t+\n292\t+\n293\t+@dataclass(frozen=True)\n294\t+class UsageRollupExportRecord:\n295\t+    \"\"\"The four columns `GET /v1/usage/export` emits — deliberately excludes\n296\t+    `event_count`, `updated_at`, and `api_key_id` (ASVS 15.3.1 minimal-\n297\t+    projection rule; the caller's identity is never echoed back).\"\"\"\n298\t+\n299\t+    customer_id: str\n300\t+    metric: str\n301\t+    window_start: datetime\n302\t+    total_quantity: Decimal\n303\t+\n304\t+\n305\t+def _export_filter_clause_and_params(\n306\t+    *,\n307\t+    api_key_id: int,\n308\t+    customer_id: str | None,\n309\t+    metric: str | None,\n310\t+    window_from: datetime | None,\n311\t+    window_to: datetime | None,\n312\t+) -> tuple[str, dict]:\n313\t+    \"\"\"Build the shared WHERE clause + bound-parameter dict for the export\n314\t+    count and stream queries, so the two statements can never drift apart.\n315\t+\n316\t+    Every fragment is a fixed literal chosen only by which filters are\n317\t+    *present*; the filter *values* always travel as bound parameters, never\n318\t+    concatenated into the SQL string.\n319\t+    \"\"\"\n320\t+    clauses = [\"api_key_id = :api_key_id\"]\n321\t+    params: dict = {\"api_key_id\": api_key_id}\n322\t+    if customer_id is not None:\n323\t+        clauses.append(\"customer_id = :customer_id\")\n324\t+        params[\"customer_id\"] = customer_id\n325\t+    if metric is not None:\n326\t+        clauses.append(\"metric = :metric\")\n327\t+        params[\"metric\"] = metric\n328\t+    if window_from is not None:\n329\t+        clauses.append(\"window_start >= :window_from\")\n330\t+        params[\"window_from\"] = window_from\n331\t+    if window_to is not None:\n332\t+        clauses.append(\"window_start <= :window_to\")\n333\t+        params[\"window_to\"] = window_to\n334\t+    return \" AND \".join(clauses), params\n335\t+\n336\t+\n337\t+async def count_usage_rollups(\n338\t+    session: AsyncSession,\n339\t+    *,\n340\t+    api_key_id: int,\n341\t+    customer_id: str | None = None,\n342\t+    metric: str | None = None,\n343\t+    window_from: datetime | None = None,\n344\t+    window_to: datetime | None = None,\n345\t+) -> int:\n346\t+    \"\"\"Count the caller's rollup rows matching the optional filters.\n347\t+\n348\t+    Backs the export's pre-flight row-cap check (AC8) — an index-prefix scan\n349\t+    on `api_key_id`, scoped first (row-level-security invariant), cheap even\n350\t+    without a covering index on the export's ORDER BY (see the plan's\n351\t+    \"Ordering vs. index\" tradeoff writeup).\n352\t+    \"\"\"\n353\t+    where_clause, params = _export_filter_clause_and_params(\n354\t+        api_key_id=api_key_id,\n355\t+        customer_id=customer_id,\n356\t+        metric=metric,\n357\t+        window_from=window_from,\n358\t+        window_to=window_to,\n359\t+    )\n360\t+    result = await session.execute(text(f\"SELECT count(*) FROM usage_rollup WHERE {where_clause}\"), params)\n361\t+    return result.scalar_one()\n362\t+\n363\t+\n364\t+# Rows fetched per server-side-cursor round-trip in `stream_usage_rollups`.\n365\t+# Bounds the client-side buffer (at most one batch is held, regardless of the\n366\t+# total result size — the constant-memory streaming invariant is preserved) and\n367\t+# trades a handful of extra rows of memory for far fewer cursor round-trips when\n368\t+# draining a large export.\n369\t+_STREAM_FETCH_BATCH = 5000\n370\t+\n371\t+\n372\t+async def stream_usage_rollups(\n373\t+    session: AsyncSession,\n374\t+    *,\n375\t+    api_key_id: int,\n376\t+    customer_id: str | None = None,\n377\t+    metric: str | None = None,\n378\t+    window_from: datetime | None = None,\n379\t+    window_to: datetime | None = None,\n380\t+    limit: int,\n381\t+) -> AsyncIterator[UsageRollupExportRecord]:\n382\t+    \"\"\"Stream the caller's rollup rows matching the optional filters via a\n383\t+    server-side cursor, in deterministic order (AC9, AC13).\n384\t+\n385\t+    The `ORDER BY` clause is a fixed literal built from server-side column\n386\t+    names, never derived from client input, so the sort key is not a\n387\t+    tampering sink. `session.stream(...)` fetches from PostgreSQL via a\n388\t+    server-side cursor rather than buffering the whole result client-side —\n389\t+    the property the constant-memory streaming design depends on.\n390\t+\n391\t+    `yield_per` tunes *how many* rows that server-side cursor fetches per\n392\t+    round-trip (it does not abandon the cursor): the default single-row/small\n393\t+    partition fetch cost ~1s to drain 100,000 rows, versus ~0.6s at\n394\t+    `_STREAM_FETCH_BATCH`, while keeping memory bounded — at most one batch of\n395\t+    rows is buffered client-side, independent of the total result size.\n396\t+    \"\"\"\n397\t+    where_clause, params = _export_filter_clause_and_params(\n398\t+        api_key_id=api_key_id,\n399\t+        customer_id=customer_id,\n400\t+        metric=metric,\n401\t+        window_from=window_from,\n402\t+        window_to=window_to,\n403\t+    )\n404\t+    params[\"limit\"] = limit\n405\t+    result = await session.stream(\n406\t+        text(\n407\t+            f\"\"\"\n408\t+            SELECT customer_id, metric, window_start, total_quantity\n409\t+            FROM usage_rollup\n410\t+            WHERE {where_clause}\n411\t+            ORDER BY window_start, customer_id, metric ASC\n412\t+            LIMIT :limit\n413\t+            \"\"\"\n414\t+        ).execution_options(yield_per=_STREAM_FETCH_BATCH),\n415\t+        params,\n416\t+    )\n417\t+    async for row in result.mappings():\n418\t+        yield UsageRollupExportRecord(\n419\t+            customer_id=row[\"customer_id\"],\n420\t+            metric=row[\"metric\"],\n421\t+            window_start=row[\"window_start\"],\n422\t+            total_quantity=row[\"total_quantity\"],\n423\t+        )\n424\tdiff --git a/src/services/README.md b/src/services/README.md\n425\tindex eb0f486..c7aacf6 100644\n426\t--- a/src/services/README.md\n427\t+++ b/src/services/README.md\n428\t@@ -9,20 +9,22 @@ Business logic layer: event ingestion (with idempotency and counter atomicity),\n429\t | File / Module | Responsibility |\n430\t |---|---|\n431\t | `events_service.py` | `create_event(principal, payload)` — inserts an event, checks the caller's quota (if any) on the winning-insert branch, and increments the hourly counter, all in one transaction; idempotent on `idempotency_key`. Raises `QuotaExceededError` (429 `quota_exceeded`) when `R + Q > L`, which rolls back the event insert. Returns the created/replayed event. |\n432\t-| `usage_service.py` | `read_usage(api_key_id, customer_id, metric, window)` — reads the aggregated counter for a time bucket; returns zeros if the bucket is empty (never 404). |\n433\t+| `usage_service.py` | `get_usage(principal, query)` — reads the aggregated counter for the `(customer_id, metric, window)` bucket in `query` (a `UsageQueryParams`); returns zeros if the bucket is empty (never 404). |\n434\t+| `usage_export_service.py` | `prepare_export(principal, params)` — the pre-flight row-cap check: a `COUNT(*)` in its own transaction, raising a plain 422 `HTTPException` over `MAX_EXPORT_ROWS` (100,000) *before* any response byte; any other (non-cap) error propagates uncaught to the error-envelope boundary (fail-closed 500, no stream ever started). `stream_export_csv(principal, params)` — the `StreamingResponse` body generator: opens its own tenant-scoped transaction (Starlette pulls it only after the route returns), yields the header row first always (so an empty result is a 200 header-only CSV, never 404), then one CSV-encoded row per streamed rollup at constant memory (a reused `io.StringIO`, drained and reset per row), and logs one `usage.export` audit event in a `finally` block (fires even on a client disconnect or a mid-stream error). |\n435\t | `quota_service.py` | `upsert_tenant_quota(principal, payload)` — create-or-replaces the caller's cap for `(customer_id, metric)` in one transaction; maps the repository's insert-vs-replace signal to 201/200 and logs the `quota.upsert` audit event. |\n436\t-| `time_windows.py` | `window_start_utc(ts: datetime)` — floors a timezone-aware timestamp to the hour (UTC); used by all three services. |\n437\t+| `time_windows.py` | `floor_to_hour_utc(timestamp: datetime)` — floors a timezone-aware timestamp to the hour (UTC); used by `events_service` and `usage_service`. |\n438\t \n439\t ## Relationships\n440\t \n441\t **Public surface:**\n442\t-- Imported by `src/api.routes.{events, usage, quotas}` to execute the core business operations.\n443\t+- Imported by `src/api.routes.{events, usage, usage_export, quotas}` to execute the core business operations.\n444\t \n445\t **Dependencies:**\n446\t - `events_service` imports `src/repositories.{events_repo, quotas_repo}` to insert the event, check the quota, and upsert the counter.\n447\t - `usage_service` imports `src/repositories.usage_repo` to read the rollup.\n448\t+- `usage_export_service` imports `src/repositories.usage_repo` (`count_usage_rollups`, `stream_usage_rollups`) and `src/api/csv_export.py` (the column contract + formula-escape facade) — it owns the `csv.writer`/`io.StringIO` streaming mechanics, `csv_export.py` owns only the encoding/escaping contract.\n449\t - `quota_service` imports `src/repositories.quotas_repo` to upsert the cap.\n450\t-- All three services receive an authenticated `AuthenticatedPrincipal` from the route handler (set by `require_api_key` guard); `principal.scope` gates `PUT /v1/quotas` at the route layer before `quota_service` ever runs.\n451\t+- All services receive an authenticated `AuthenticatedPrincipal` from the route handler (set by `require_api_key` guard); `principal.scope` gates `PUT /v1/quotas` at the route layer before `quota_service` ever runs (the export has no scope gate — any authenticated key may export its own tenant's data).\n452\t - `time_windows` is imported by `events_service` and `usage_service` to floor timestamps.\n453\t \n454\t **Transaction boundary:**\n455\tdiff --git a/tests/README.md b/tests/README.md\n456\tindex 0a6d78b..9860087 100644\n457\t--- a/tests/README.md\n458\t+++ b/tests/README.md\n459\t@@ -15,6 +15,7 @@ unit tests here, endpoint/migration/concurrency/perf tests under `integration/`.\n460\t | `test_app_smoke.py` | App-construction-level tests needing no DB/Redis: liveness, OpenAPI exposure, unauthenticated-denial/error-envelope shape. |\n461\t | `test_auth_api_key.py` | Split-token parsing and the in-process verification cache (Argon2id-vs-p95 cache mechanism). |\n462\t | `test_crypto.py` | `src/crypto` facade: Argon2id hash/verify, constant-time compare. |\n463\t+| `test_csv_export.py` | `src/api/csv_export.py` unit tests: `escape_csv_text_cell` (formula-trigger prefixing incl. leading-`-` `customer_id`, control-char stripping), RFC 4180 quoting via `csv.writer`, `format_window_start`/`format_total_quantity` value formatting (no scientific notation, UTC ISO-8601). |\n464\t | `test_dast_context_documented.py` | Asserts the DAST scanner auth context (header + token shape) is documented somewhere a DAST job's config can read it. |\n465\t | `test_db_session_isolation.py` | Regression guard for the `READ COMMITTED` isolation pin in `src/db/session.py` — the dependency the quota lock-then-read atomicity in `src/repositories/quotas_repo.py::read_tenant_quota_state_locked` relies on. |\n466\t | `test_dependency_pins.py` | Security-regression guard against a starlette CVE-carrying downgrade (pinned version stays at the patched release). |\n467\t@@ -23,8 +24,10 @@ unit tests here, endpoint/migration/concurrency/perf tests under `integration/`.\n468\t | `test_schemas_events.py` | Validation-contract tests for `EventCreateRequest`. |\n469\t | `test_schemas_quotas.py` | Validation-contract tests for `QuotaPutRequest` (anchored `customer_id`/`metric` allowlists, `limit_per_window` bounds, injection rejection). |\n470\t | `test_schemas_usage.py` | Validation-contract tests for `UsageQueryParams`. |\n471\t+| `test_schemas_usage_export.py` | Validation-contract tests for `UsageExportQueryParams`: all-filters-optional, the `from`/`from_` alias binding, naive-datetime rejection, `from<=to` and `[now-90d, now+1h]` bound enforcement, `extra=\"forbid\"` rejecting unknown/injected fields. |\n472\t | `test_slo_alarms_defined.py` | Static assertion that the declared SLO burn-rate + canary CloudWatch alarms exist in the Terraform source with the exact names `deploy.yml` expects. |\n473\t-| `test_time_windows.py` | Tests for the UTC hour-flooring helper (`window_start_utc`) shared by `events_service`, `usage_service`, and `quota_service`. |\n474\t+| `test_time_windows.py` | Tests for the UTC hour-flooring helper (`floor_to_hour_utc`) shared by `events_service` and `usage_service`. |\n475\t+| `test_usage_export_service.py` | `src/services/usage_export_service.py` unit tests: `prepare_export` cap-boundary (exactly-at-cap passes, cap+1 → 422) and fail-closed non-cap-error propagation (AC22); `stream_export_csv` header-first-on-empty-result, audit-log fields (no raw `customer_id`), `completed=False` on a mid-stream failure, and the chunk-batching regression guard (`_ROWS_PER_CHUNK`). |\n476\t | `integration/` | Tests requiring a real Postgres/Redis (testcontainers) or a live HTTP process — see `tests/integration/README.md`. |\n477\t \n478\t ## Relationships\n479\tdiff --git a/tests/integration/README.md b/tests/integration/README.md\n480\tindex 4dbdf4d..a19bbec 100644\n481\t--- a/tests/integration/README.md\n482\t+++ b/tests/integration/README.md\n483\t@@ -27,6 +27,8 @@ suite in `tests/` (no live DB/Redis there).\n484\t | `test_rate_limit.py` | Tier-2 (`api_key_id`-keyed) rate limiting: two principals on one IP get independent buckets; one principal across two IPs shares one bucket. |\n485\t | `test_seed_api_key_script.py` | `scripts/seed_api_key.py` provisions a key against a real database, including the `--admin` flag setting `scope='admin'` (default `scope='ingest'`). |\n486\t | `test_usage_endpoint.py` | `GET /v1/usage` integration tests (aggregation, tenant isolation). |\n487\t+| `test_usage_export_endpoint.py` | `GET /v1/usage/export` integration tests: header-only-CSV on an empty result, per-filter narrowing, deterministic ordering, two-tenant isolation, row-cap 422 with no partial body, formula-injection escape end-to-end, response headers (content-type/filename/nosniff/no-store), streaming-not-buffered (multi-chunk) sanity, OpenAPI-schema exposure (AC19), the seeded DAST key calling the export via `test_export_seeded_dast_key_can_call_the_export` (AC20), and the fail-closed pre-flight 500 on a forced `COUNT` error (AC22). |\n488\t+| `test_usage_export_perf.py` | Real-Postgres-testcontainer p95 timing sanity check for the export at the 100,000-row cap (AC16) — a 10-sample stable measurement asserting the human-confirmed `p95 <= 3,000ms` bound (not a k6 load test). |\n489\t | `k6/` | k6 load-test scripts driven by `test_perf_k6_load.py` — see `k6/README.md`. |\n490\t \n491\t ## Relationships\n492\t"}]},"uuid":"946d81da-6b18-427d-849a-b639406744cc","timestamp":"2026-07-09T20:47:44.437Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"b71cb34b-2e55-4749-b0d7-e9b3b5ccb9b6","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/usage-export"}
